00:12:05.050 --> 00:12:09.790
So we definitely see
differences in what

00:12:09.790 --> 00:12:13.810
the patient's hormonal
balance is as it relates

00:12:13.810 --> 00:12:15.200
to storing and sleep apnea.

00:12:15.200 --> 00:12:18.590
So someone with a high
testosterone content

00:12:18.590 --> 00:12:20.590
is going to be more
predicated to having snoring

00:12:20.590 --> 00:12:21.670
and sleep apnea.

00:12:21.670 --> 00:12:24.340
And that's why when
women go into menopause,

00:12:24.340 --> 00:12:26.500
we see a shift in the
balance of their hormones

00:12:26.500 --> 00:12:31.030
more into testosterone, and then
we see more apneas, typically.

00:12:31.030 --> 00:12:33.760
Hypertension, it's very common.

00:12:33.760 --> 00:12:36.760
People that have uncontrolled
hypertension, meaning they

00:12:36.760 --> 00:12:39.250
tried one or two
or more medications

00:12:39.250 --> 00:12:43.280
and it only puts a dent in their
blood pressure, very commonly,

00:12:43.280 --> 00:12:45.730
at least 80% of the time,
it's the apnea that's

00:12:45.730 --> 00:12:48.920
causing the hypertension.

00:12:48.920 --> 00:12:51.130
Obesity, it goes both ways.

00:12:51.130 --> 00:12:54.010
Like I mentioned, being obese
can cause you to have snoring

00:12:54.010 --> 00:12:57.880
and sleep apnea, but can
actually take whatever you have

00:12:57.880 --> 00:12:59.140
and make it worse.

00:12:59.140 --> 00:13:00.830
We see that more commonly.

00:13:00.830 --> 00:13:04.420
But also, when you're getting
interrupted sleep, when

00:13:04.420 --> 00:13:07.270
you wake up, you're more
tired, and therefore you

00:13:07.270 --> 00:13:08.980
want to eat more.

00:13:08.980 --> 00:13:11.110
And you're not conscious
that you want to eat more.

00:13:11.110 --> 00:13:12.340
You just eat more.

00:13:12.340 --> 00:13:15.623
And that contributes to obesity,
because you're eating more

00:13:15.623 --> 00:13:16.790
calories throughout the day.

00:13:16.790 --> 00:13:17.880
WENDY JUDSON: And that's
a hormonal changes

00:13:17.880 --> 00:13:18.380
that occurs, right?

00:13:18.380 --> 00:13:19.350
DAVE SHIRAZI: And that's
a hormonal change, yeah,

00:13:19.350 --> 00:13:20.058
with the ghrelin.

00:13:20.058 --> 00:13:20.860
Exactly.

00:13:20.860 --> 00:13:21.730
Morning headaches.

00:13:21.730 --> 00:13:24.010
That can go in two
different directions.

00:13:24.010 --> 00:13:26.890
If you have the kind of
headaches where you wake up

00:13:26.890 --> 00:13:28.990
feeling kind of like
an empty head, that's

00:13:28.990 --> 00:13:32.440
usually more from an
oxygen deprivation, I find.

00:13:32.440 --> 00:13:35.860
Tension type headaches, which
is the most common headaches

00:13:35.860 --> 00:13:38.020
in the world,
that's predominantly

00:13:38.020 --> 00:13:40.360
caused by clenching
your teeth and how

00:13:40.360 --> 00:13:42.790
it pinches on the nerves
in the back of the skull.

00:13:42.790 --> 00:13:44.980
And like I said, the number
one cause of clenching

00:13:44.980 --> 00:13:48.670
is some form of upper
airway disturbance.

00:13:48.670 --> 00:13:50.000
Type 2 diabetes.

00:13:50.000 --> 00:13:54.340
We have direct, not just
correlational, but causal

00:13:54.340 --> 00:13:57.550
research that shows that
the inflammation that's

00:13:57.550 --> 00:14:03.350
caused from sleep apnea can
lead to type 2 diabetes.

00:14:03.350 --> 00:14:05.860
And we'll actually see these
very same patients being

00:14:05.860 --> 00:14:09.010
treated with either CPAP
or oral appliance therapy

00:14:09.010 --> 00:14:11.862
and their blood sugar is
coming down without medication.

00:14:11.862 --> 00:14:13.570
So we know there's a
causal relationship.

00:14:13.570 --> 00:14:15.340
We don't say it's
the only cause,

00:14:15.340 --> 00:14:17.795
but we definitely see
a causal relationship.

00:14:17.795 --> 00:14:20.170
WENDY JUDSON: So I went ahead
and skipped to this slide--

00:14:20.170 --> 00:14:21.420
DAVE SHIRAZI: It's a good one.

00:14:21.420 --> 00:14:23.320
WENDY JUDSON: --that
shows the correlation,

00:14:23.320 --> 00:14:24.760
just since we're
discussing that.

00:14:24.760 --> 00:14:26.630
We can hop back after that.

00:14:26.630 --> 00:14:30.490
But this shows some
of the hormones

00:14:30.490 --> 00:14:33.980
that are released or disturbed.

00:14:33.980 --> 00:14:36.100
DAVE SHIRAZI: That's right.

00:14:36.100 --> 00:14:39.610
So this slide is very
much a condensation.

00:14:39.610 --> 00:14:42.940
There is a whole physiological
cascade that's going on.

00:14:42.940 --> 00:14:46.090
But from the oxygen
deprivation, we

00:14:46.090 --> 00:14:48.310
have the repetitive hypoxemia.

00:14:48.310 --> 00:14:50.290
You go through
moments of low oxygen.

00:14:50.290 --> 00:14:55.120
But more important to that is
that sleep fragmentation, what

00:14:55.120 --> 00:14:57.490
we call the arousal index.

00:14:57.490 --> 00:15:01.000
It's the arousals that actually
cause the inflammation what

00:15:01.000 --> 00:15:02.050
we're finding.

00:15:02.050 --> 00:15:06.040
So your arousals can come from
your own snoring or sleep apnea

00:15:06.040 --> 00:15:08.480
or they can come from your bed
partner's snoring and sleep

00:15:08.480 --> 00:15:08.980
apnea.

00:15:08.980 --> 00:15:11.450
It can come from a
noisy neighbor's dog,

00:15:11.450 --> 00:15:14.610
from construction, from a
dog or a cat in your bed

00:15:14.610 --> 00:15:18.490
that's constantly jostling or
they themselves are snoring.

00:15:18.490 --> 00:15:20.180
That can cause
the fragmentation.

00:15:20.180 --> 00:15:22.300
So what the
fragmentation does is

00:15:22.300 --> 00:15:24.520
it causes the sympathetic
nerve activity.

00:15:24.520 --> 00:15:26.920
We go into fight or flight.

00:15:26.920 --> 00:15:29.050
And that causes the
cytokine release.

00:15:29.050 --> 00:15:31.630
Well, cytokine release is
just an inflammatory cascade.

00:15:31.630 --> 00:15:33.280
It could be not just cytokines.

00:15:33.280 --> 00:15:34.630
Could be interleukins.

00:15:34.630 --> 00:15:36.130
It could be C reactive protein.

00:15:36.130 --> 00:15:37.540
It could be TNF alpha.

00:15:37.540 --> 00:15:40.660
But all of those
inflammatory markers

00:15:40.660 --> 00:15:42.790
will cause us to
become hungrier,

00:15:42.790 --> 00:15:45.970
will cause our sugar to spike,
will cause, like we said,

00:15:45.970 --> 00:15:48.640
hypertension, can
lead to-- we now

00:15:48.640 --> 00:15:52.300
are discovering that depression
is more an inflammatory disease

00:15:52.300 --> 00:15:54.160
than it is anything else.

00:15:54.160 --> 00:15:56.350
WENDY JUDSON: So
really a lot of us

00:15:56.350 --> 00:15:58.630
are walking around with a
low level of inflammation

00:15:58.630 --> 00:15:59.890
that we're not even aware of.

00:15:59.890 --> 00:16:02.080
DAVE SHIRAZI: A high level
of inflammation and not aware

00:16:02.080 --> 00:16:02.570
of it.

00:16:02.570 --> 00:16:04.237
And then on top of
it, this inflammation

00:16:04.237 --> 00:16:06.880
causes our blood
brain barrier to open.

00:16:06.880 --> 00:16:08.920
So now all these
inflammatory markers

00:16:08.920 --> 00:16:12.610
and whatever you ate that day or
drank that night that you maybe

00:16:12.610 --> 00:16:15.790
shouldn't have eaten or drank,
now has the ability to get up

00:16:15.790 --> 00:16:18.563
into the spinal fluid.

00:16:18.563 --> 00:16:20.980
And then you have the weight
gain, the insulin resistance,

00:16:20.980 --> 00:16:22.250
the type 2 diabetes.

00:16:22.250 --> 00:16:25.727
But then that also contributes
to more sleep apnea,

00:16:25.727 --> 00:16:27.310
because you can
either have the weight

00:16:27.310 --> 00:16:29.680
gain from just
gain of fat or you

00:16:29.680 --> 00:16:32.770
can have the weight gain because
you're retaining more fluid.

00:16:32.770 --> 00:16:35.830
And if you have more fluid
in your upper pharyngeal area

00:16:35.830 --> 00:16:39.340
or your tongue, that will also
collapse your airway at night

00:16:39.340 --> 00:16:40.620
more so.

00:16:40.620 --> 00:16:41.620
WENDY JUDSON: All right.

00:16:41.620 --> 00:16:44.710
Well, let's look at
that airway and go back

00:16:44.710 --> 00:16:47.630
on some of these slides here.

00:16:47.630 --> 00:16:51.790
So this is some of the
points of obstruction.

00:16:51.790 --> 00:16:54.970
And then we'll look
at the machinery

00:16:54.970 --> 00:16:57.508
that you use to
diagnose patients.

00:16:57.508 --> 00:16:58.300
DAVE SHIRAZI: Yeah.

00:16:58.300 --> 00:17:02.170
So we have four points of
occlusion in obstructive sleep

00:17:02.170 --> 00:17:03.010
apnea.

00:17:03.010 --> 00:17:05.050
We have our nasal breathing.

00:17:05.050 --> 00:17:06.910
And predominantly,
in my observation,

00:17:06.910 --> 00:17:09.970
nasal breathing has to do
with the internal nasal valves

00:17:09.970 --> 00:17:14.000
and the turbinate space,
the adenoidal soft tissue,

00:17:14.000 --> 00:17:17.619
soft palate area, the tongue,
and the intrapharyngeal space

00:17:17.619 --> 00:17:18.890
or throat.

00:17:18.890 --> 00:17:23.710
So any or all of those
can be causal or affected,

00:17:23.710 --> 00:17:25.958
and they're all
related to each other.

00:17:25.958 --> 00:17:28.000
So like we talked about,
if someone can't breathe

00:17:28.000 --> 00:17:29.583
through their nose,
they automatically

00:17:29.583 --> 00:17:31.300
mouth breathe, which
shifts the position

00:17:31.300 --> 00:17:33.180
of their tongue and their jaw.

00:17:33.180 --> 00:17:34.240
That make sense?

00:17:34.240 --> 00:17:38.830
If someone has a cold or a flu
and their tonsils and adenoids

00:17:38.830 --> 00:17:41.830
are inflamed, there's going
to be a change as well.

00:17:41.830 --> 00:17:44.050
WENDY JUDSON: So one
obstruction can lead to another,

00:17:44.050 --> 00:17:44.800
essentially.

00:17:44.800 --> 00:17:47.530
DAVE SHIRAZI: It's an
instantaneous physiological

00:17:47.530 --> 00:17:51.820
change in order to
survive and to breathe.

00:17:51.820 --> 00:17:54.520
WENDY JUDSON: And what is this?

00:17:54.520 --> 00:17:57.340
DAVE SHIRAZI: So we just have
a CAT scan in our office.

00:17:57.340 --> 00:18:00.020
It's what called a
cone beam CAT scan.

00:18:00.020 --> 00:18:03.270
So it uses just a
fraction of the radiation

00:18:03.270 --> 00:18:04.960
of a traditional CAT scan.

00:18:04.960 --> 00:18:06.050
It's pretty clever.

00:18:06.050 --> 00:18:07.600
Instead of a
traditional CAT scan

00:18:07.600 --> 00:18:10.360
that has 2,000 or 3,000
microsieverts of radiation,

00:18:10.360 --> 00:18:12.730
this machine goes around
your head and neck,

00:18:12.730 --> 00:18:17.210
puts a tiny burst of radiation
as it goes throughout,

00:18:17.210 --> 00:18:20.230
and then it extrapolates
that data into a three

00:18:20.230 --> 00:18:22.240
dimensional rendering.

00:18:22.240 --> 00:18:26.710
That is about 60
microsieverts of radiation.

00:18:26.710 --> 00:18:29.045
And a one way flight to New
York is 100 microsieverts

00:18:29.045 --> 00:18:29.820
of radiation.

00:18:29.820 --> 00:18:32.620
So we're talking really,
really tiny levels.

00:18:32.620 --> 00:18:34.510
And then we have the
ability to then look--

00:18:34.510 --> 00:18:35.830
you can go to the next slide--

00:18:35.830 --> 00:18:39.880
to have a look at the nose
and the throat and the airway.

00:18:39.880 --> 00:18:44.800
Now, about this slide
and about why this just

00:18:44.800 --> 00:18:46.820
gives us a picture in time.

00:18:46.820 --> 00:18:49.840
So what I'm actually
more so than the airway

00:18:49.840 --> 00:18:52.810
in this particular slide that
