Two-fold disservice.

00:23:28.030 --> 00:23:31.210
Because when we look at
skulls before the Industrial

00:23:31.210 --> 00:23:34.990
Revolution, most of
them had straight teeth.

00:23:34.990 --> 00:23:37.450
Most of them had very,
very wide palates.

00:23:37.450 --> 00:23:41.170
They had relatively small
sinuses and big nasal turbinate

00:23:41.170 --> 00:23:42.790
space.

00:23:42.790 --> 00:23:47.440
And we know that the average
breastfeeding period was

00:23:47.440 --> 00:23:50.380
between three to five years.

00:23:50.380 --> 00:23:52.600
Now, when you're
breastfeeding, if you

00:23:52.600 --> 00:23:55.480
can imagine if the nipple
is inside the child's mouth,

00:23:55.480 --> 00:23:58.750
the tongue pinches
the base of the nipple

00:23:58.750 --> 00:24:02.470
and then makes this little
rolling action over the palate,

00:24:02.470 --> 00:24:05.830
squeezes the nipple, and
gets the milk that way.

00:24:05.830 --> 00:24:08.260
And when they stop
breastfeeding,

00:24:08.260 --> 00:24:10.450
they still swallow this way.

00:24:10.450 --> 00:24:13.690
And while we're growing,
it's the tongue that actually

00:24:13.690 --> 00:24:15.460
develops the palate naturally.

00:24:15.460 --> 00:24:16.700
Does that make sense?

00:24:16.700 --> 00:24:20.230
So when we go to bottle feeding,
we have a two-fold problem.

00:24:20.230 --> 00:24:22.630
Because one, the
nipple itself is now

00:24:22.630 --> 00:24:24.880
suppressing the tongue down.

00:24:24.880 --> 00:24:28.050
And two, you're using
your buccinator muscles,

00:24:28.050 --> 00:24:31.840
that's your cheek muscles, to
swallow like this, which then

00:24:31.840 --> 00:24:36.130
narrows the palate, which then
raises the arch, which means

00:24:36.130 --> 00:24:39.280
you really don't even have space
for your tongue to go up there

00:24:39.280 --> 00:24:42.440
anymore because it's so
narrow and high arched.

00:24:42.440 --> 00:24:43.600
Does that make sense?

00:24:43.600 --> 00:24:44.392
WENDY JUDSON: Yeah.

00:24:44.392 --> 00:24:47.350
So we could reduce a whole
lot of this sleep apnea

00:24:47.350 --> 00:24:50.508
just by having children
breastfeed for a longer period.

00:24:50.508 --> 00:24:51.550
DAVE SHIRAZI: Absolutely.

00:24:51.550 --> 00:24:53.565
For sure.

00:24:53.565 --> 00:24:55.190
WENDY JUDSON: Which
you say right here.

00:24:55.190 --> 00:24:59.210
Can sometimes be
completely fixed when

00:24:59.210 --> 00:25:00.710
you discover it early enough.

00:25:00.710 --> 00:25:02.210
DAVE SHIRAZI: So that is--

00:25:02.210 --> 00:25:03.377
I'm not sure about the data.

00:25:03.377 --> 00:25:05.335
I don't know if we've
had longitudinal studies.

00:25:05.335 --> 00:25:08.270
Because you have to realize,
understanding snoring and sleep

00:25:08.270 --> 00:25:11.960
apnea has only been
going on for 40 years.

00:25:11.960 --> 00:25:14.090
Before that, it was
just Pickwickian,

00:25:14.090 --> 00:25:17.420
where we talked about the
jolly old fat man that snored

00:25:17.420 --> 00:25:19.340
and could sleep standing up.

00:25:19.340 --> 00:25:21.900
But we didn't have
knowledge of it back then.

00:25:21.900 --> 00:25:22.400
Who knows?

00:25:22.400 --> 00:25:26.660
It may not have even existed
in that kind of numbers.

00:25:26.660 --> 00:25:29.630
But the point of that
slide, that sentence,

00:25:29.630 --> 00:25:33.350
is the only time
we can technically

00:25:33.350 --> 00:25:38.720
cure sleep apnea without
surgery is in children

00:25:38.720 --> 00:25:41.720
through what's called
functional orthodontics, where

00:25:41.720 --> 00:25:44.540
we develop the palate,
develop the tongue,

00:25:44.540 --> 00:25:47.360
develop the mandible forward.

00:25:47.360 --> 00:25:48.130
That make sense?

00:25:48.130 --> 00:25:49.030
WENDY JUDSON: Yeah.

00:25:49.030 --> 00:25:50.710
And so in adults,
what we're doing

00:25:50.710 --> 00:25:55.617
is trying to just improve.

00:25:55.617 --> 00:25:56.950
DAVE SHIRAZI: We can improve it.

00:25:56.950 --> 00:25:59.410
The data is not as
conclusive as it

00:25:59.410 --> 00:26:03.352
is for children for adults
doing functional orthodontics.

00:26:03.352 --> 00:26:05.560
WENDY JUDSON: And these are
just some of the symptoms

00:26:05.560 --> 00:26:07.850
of sleep apnea in kids.

00:26:07.850 --> 00:26:11.860
So any of you who have kids
may have noticed some of these,

00:26:11.860 --> 00:26:14.098
and it might be something
you want to explore.

00:26:14.098 --> 00:26:14.890
DAVE SHIRAZI: Yeah.

00:26:14.890 --> 00:26:18.130
The most common
side effect, if you

00:26:18.130 --> 00:26:20.770
will, or symptom of
snoring and sleep apnea

00:26:20.770 --> 00:26:27.110
in children, interrupted sleep,
is hyperactivity and ADD.

00:26:27.110 --> 00:26:29.770
That's the most
common one of all.

00:26:29.770 --> 00:26:31.930
And it's because
pediatric neurology

00:26:31.930 --> 00:26:33.650
is opposite of adults.

00:26:33.650 --> 00:26:37.510
So when adults get tired
from sleep fragmentation,

00:26:37.510 --> 00:26:41.500
children get amped up and wired
and have difficulty processing

00:26:41.500 --> 00:26:44.380
things and sitting still.

00:26:44.380 --> 00:26:48.530
Defiance has actually been
overlapped with this, as well.

00:26:48.530 --> 00:26:52.330
And the number of
studies that have

00:26:52.330 --> 00:26:56.380
shown that correcting sleep
apnea or a sleep disorder

00:26:56.380 --> 00:27:00.850
breathing in the child with ADD
or ADHD and then it resolves it

00:27:00.850 --> 00:27:03.010
is in the thousands.

00:27:03.010 --> 00:27:04.550
It's not a secret.

00:27:04.550 --> 00:27:06.130
It's not talked
about, unfortunately.

00:27:06.130 --> 00:27:08.470
Most pediatricians, if
you ask them about it,

00:27:08.470 --> 00:27:10.420
they would be kind
of blase about it.

00:27:10.420 --> 00:27:15.040
But it's something that's well
established in the literature.

00:27:15.040 --> 00:27:17.530
And every child should
be screened for snoring

00:27:17.530 --> 00:27:19.970
and sleep apnea,
without exemption.

00:27:19.970 --> 00:27:21.910
WENDY JUDSON: OK.

00:27:21.910 --> 00:27:24.448
Now what about in the elderly?

00:27:24.448 --> 00:27:25.240
DAVE SHIRAZI: Yeah.

00:27:25.240 --> 00:27:28.500
The elderly, of
course, need snoring--

00:27:28.500 --> 00:27:30.190
sleeping as well, sorry.

00:27:30.190 --> 00:27:34.630
But they need less sleep than
children or even adults do.

00:27:34.630 --> 00:27:37.930
But their sleep has
changed, depending

00:27:37.930 --> 00:27:40.060
on how active they are.

00:27:40.060 --> 00:27:43.060
So when we see the
elderly population,

00:27:43.060 --> 00:27:46.180
but they're still teaching
at the university level,

00:27:46.180 --> 00:27:48.040
they're still physically
active, they're

00:27:48.040 --> 00:27:50.950
still getting good
amounts of REM and delta.

00:27:50.950 --> 00:27:55.330
The ones that aren't,
we see much less sleep.

00:27:55.330 --> 00:27:57.070
And in that population,
we're seeing

00:27:57.070 --> 00:27:59.740
a lot of other
neurological diseases being

00:27:59.740 --> 00:28:00.610
overlapped to it.

00:28:00.610 --> 00:28:05.170
Because instead of getting
hyperactivity and ADD,

00:28:05.170 --> 00:28:07.690
we're seeing in the elderly
neurodegenerative disorders

00:28:07.690 --> 00:28:10.053
like Parkinson's
and Alzheimer's.

00:28:10.053 --> 00:28:11.970
WENDY JUDSON: So we could
avoid some of those.

00:28:11.970 --> 00:28:13.303
DAVE SHIRAZI: Potentially, yeah.

00:28:13.303 --> 00:28:16.870
So Alzheimer's has been called,
in the last 10 years, type 3

00:28:16.870 --> 00:28:19.930
diabetes because
of the relationship

00:28:19.930 --> 00:28:22.310
between their inflammation
and their sugar levels,

00:28:22.310 --> 00:28:25.760
which my father had, by the way.

00:28:25.760 --> 00:28:28.180
So we already know
the relationship

00:28:28.180 --> 00:28:33.910
between insulin resistance
and diabetes with sleep apnea.

00:28:33.910 --> 00:28:37.150
It's not a far cry to
say, OK, here it is,

00:28:37.150 --> 00:28:38.680
relationship with Alzheimer's.

00:28:38.680 --> 00:28:40.180
WENDY JUDSON: So
taking care of this

00:28:40.180 --> 00:28:41.918
now can really help
us in the future.

00:28:41.918 --> 00:28:42.710
DAVE SHIRAZI: Yeah.

00:28:42.710 --> 00:28:43.600
WENDY JUDSON: This
is hard to read,

00:28:43.600 --> 00:28:45.160
so I'm just going to skip by it.

00:28:45.160 --> 00:28:46.570
DAVE SHIRAZI: No worries.

00:28:46.570 --> 00:28:50.380
WENDY JUDSON: Moving on
now to the TMJ or TMD.

00:28:50.380 --> 00:28:55.120
Can you clarify what
is the appropriate term

00:28:55.120 --> 00:28:57.580
to talk about problems with TMJ?

00:28:57.580 --> 00:29:00.010
DAVE SHIRAZI: You hear so
many times, I have TMJ.

00:29:00.010 --> 00:29:02.740
OK, so TMJ is just the
name of the anatomy.

00:29:02.740 --> 00:29:03.760
Temporomandibular.

00:29:03.760 --> 00:29:05.590
Everyone has a TMJ.

00:29:05.590 --> 00:29:10.060
TMJ disorder is some sort of
dysfunction associated with it,

00:29:10.060 --> 00:29:15.610
whether it's a
dislocation, a broken

00:29:15.610 --> 00:29:20.260
jaw, like a fractured jaw and
neck, arthritis, effusion,

00:29:20.260 --> 00:29:21.710
swelling of the joint.

00:29:21.710 --> 00:29:24.670
It could be a disorder
that falls in there.

00:29:24.670 --> 00:29:27.820
So that, nomenclature
wise, the word TMJ

00:29:27.820 --> 00:29:30.120
just means the anatomy.

00:29:30.120 --> 00:29:34.190
WENDY JUDSON: And the TMD is
the actual disorder or problem

00:29:34.190 --> 00:29:34.690
with it?

00:29:34.690 --> 00:29:35.815
DAVE SHIRAZI: That's right.

00:29:35.815 --> 00:29:37.570
And then it's sort
of like cancer, where

00:29:37.570 --> 00:29:41.500
you have stage one, stage two,
stage three, metastatic or not.

00:29:41.500 --> 00:29:46.120
It's like we subdivide
different TMJ disorders.

00:29:46.120 --> 00:29:48.340
WENDY JUDSON: And we
kind of spoke about this,

00:29:48.340 --> 00:29:52.170
but the tongue moving
appropriately in the mouth

00:29:52.170 --> 00:29:56.640
is definitely connected
to this TMD problem.

00:29:56.640 --> 00:29:58.390
DAVE SHIRAZI: Yeah,
so if you can imagine,

00:29:58.390 --> 00:30:01.780
if you're swallowing
properly, if your tongue is

00:30:01.780 --> 00:30:04.640
coming forward and
swallowing properly,

00:30:04.640 --> 00:30:07.630
it's going to bring
the mandible with it.

00:30:07.630 --> 00:30:10.570
But if on the other hand, while
you're sleeping, let's say,

00:30:10.570 --> 00:30:12.572
your tongue is tethered
to your mandible

00:30:12.572 --> 00:30:14.030
while you're sleeping
on your back,

00:30:14.030 --> 00:30:15.460
you've effectively
doubled the weight

00:30:15.460 --> 00:30:17.140
of your mandible,
which will close off

00:30:17.140 --> 00:30:18.100
the airway a bit more.

00:30:18.100 --> 00:30:19.430
Does that make sense?

00:30:19.430 --> 00:30:19.930
Yeah.

00:30:19.930 --> 00:30:23.290
That's very, very hard to
decipher through literature.

00:30:23.290 --> 00:30:25.540
But we see it.

00:30:25.540 --> 00:30:28.480
There are a countless number
of studies where they actually

00:30:28.480 --> 00:30:31.150
do what's called myofunctional
therapy, where they train you

00:30:31.150 --> 00:30:33.100
how to swallow properly
when your tongue is

00:30:33.100 --> 00:30:34.870
too low on your mandible.

00:30:34.870 --> 00:30:39.310
And they'll show a 50% reduction
in AHI scores of the snoring

00:30:39.310 --> 00:30:40.060
and sleep.

00:30:40.060 --> 00:30:41.410
WENDY JUDSON: AHI scores?

00:30:41.410 --> 00:30:44.000
DAVE SHIRAZI: So that's our
metric for measuring sleep

00:30:44.000 --> 00:30:44.980
apnea.

00:30:44.980 --> 00:30:49.030
A stands for Apnea, when your
airway is closed for 10 seconds

00:30:49.030 --> 00:30:50.090
or longer.

00:30:50.090 --> 00:30:53.470
H stands for Hypopnea,
when your breathing

00:30:53.470 --> 00:30:58.840
is so shallow that it
causes your oxygen to dip 3%

00:30:58.840 --> 00:30:59.710
or greater.

00:30:59.710 --> 00:31:01.305
And the I stands
for Index, which

00:31:01.305 --> 00:31:05.620
is the number of times
per hour you do the both.

00:31:05.620 --> 00:31:07.810
WENDY JUDSON: So then
correcting this problem,

00:31:07.810 --> 00:31:12.970
what really surprised me is
that the posture can change.

00:31:12.970 --> 00:31:16.540
So this forward head
posture that I work on a lot

00:31:16.540 --> 00:31:21.310
can actually be mitigated
by addressing TMD.

00:31:21.310 --> 00:31:23.560
DAVE SHIRAZI: It depends if
you have both that posture

00:31:23.560 --> 00:31:25.940
and you have a TMD
at the same time.

00:31:25.940 --> 00:31:29.530
So if this is your
ergonomics all day,

00:31:29.530 --> 00:31:33.170
I don't know how much TMJ
therapy is going to help you.

00:31:33.170 --> 00:31:36.820
But if you have a TM problem, if
you are mouth breathing, which

00:31:36.820 --> 00:31:39.970
is one of the main reasons why
we have forward head posture,

00:31:39.970 --> 00:31:43.305
and then you add a poor
ergonomic situation where

00:31:43.305 --> 00:31:45.430
you're doing this or you're
on your phone like this

00:31:45.430 --> 00:31:48.760
all the time, that is
definitely going to compound it.

00:31:48.760 --> 00:31:52.390
WENDY JUDSON: So we
have a study here

00:31:52.390 --> 00:31:55.390
and showed that a higher
proportion of headache patients

00:31:55.390 --> 00:31:58.210
diagnosed with TMJ
pain, they also

00:31:58.210 --> 00:32:02.590
reported more frequent
and intense tooth contact,

00:32:02.590 --> 00:32:05.590
more masticatory muscle
tension, stress, and pain

00:32:05.590 --> 00:32:07.900
in the face, head, and
other parts of the body

00:32:07.900 --> 00:32:09.676
than the non-headache controls.

00:32:09.676 --> 00:32:10.550
DAVE SHIRAZI: Yeah.

00:32:10.550 --> 00:32:14.340
This is something we also
commonly see in the literature.

00:32:14.340 --> 00:32:17.530
Again, we're probably past
2,000 studies as well,

00:32:17.530 --> 00:32:21.070
where we see those with both
tension type and migraine type

00:32:21.070 --> 00:32:29.220
headaches have much more TMJ and
clenching problems than norms,

00:32:29.220 --> 00:32:32.190
than just people in
the normal population.

00:32:32.190 --> 00:32:34.160
And then we also
see studies that

00:32:34.160 --> 00:32:38.450
show that when you address the
TMJ disorder, they're both--

00:32:38.450 --> 00:32:41.780
either their tension type
headaches completely go away

00:32:41.780 --> 00:32:44.330
or their migraine type
headaches can potentially

00:32:44.330 --> 00:32:46.850
reduce substantially.

00:32:46.850 --> 00:32:49.770
So we definitely
see that overlap.

00:32:49.770 --> 00:32:51.390
WENDY JUDSON: That was great.

00:32:51.390 --> 00:32:56.430
So here you might want to talk
a little bit about this slide

00:32:56.430 --> 00:33:00.962
and what is a migraine as
compared to another headache.

00:33:00.962 --> 00:33:02.420
DAVE SHIRAZI: Yeah,
very different.

00:33:02.420 --> 00:33:06.500
So a tension type headache,
when we're actually clenching,

00:33:06.500 --> 00:33:09.170
imagine all these muscles, not
just the clenching muscles,

00:33:09.170 --> 00:33:12.300
but of the neck just
all going like this.

00:33:12.300 --> 00:33:16.560
We actually see a compression
of the greater occipital

00:33:16.560 --> 00:33:19.550
and greater oracular nerves
at the base of the skull,

00:33:19.550 --> 00:33:23.570
and it comes across here, and
it can feel like a vise grip.

00:33:23.570 --> 00:33:25.670
And sometimes people will
experience, they'll say,

00:33:25.670 --> 00:33:27.170
oh, I went to my chiropractor.

00:33:27.170 --> 00:33:29.270
They adjusted my neck and
my tension type headache

00:33:29.270 --> 00:33:30.590
went away immediately.

00:33:30.590 --> 00:33:33.500
And then I slept and then the
next morning it came back.

00:33:33.500 --> 00:33:34.990
It didn't hold.

00:33:34.990 --> 00:33:37.340
But when it was in fact
the clenching that kind of

00:33:37.340 --> 00:33:38.150
led to it.

00:33:38.150 --> 00:33:40.190
Migraine type headache.

00:33:40.190 --> 00:33:45.170
So a migraine is what we call a
centrally sensitized disorder.

00:33:45.170 --> 00:33:47.870
And what that means
is you all understand

00:33:47.870 --> 00:33:49.580
what referred pain is, right?

00:33:49.580 --> 00:33:52.250
You have a pinch in your neck
and it makes your arm hurt.

00:33:52.250 --> 00:33:54.500
That's referred
pain down your arm.

00:33:54.500 --> 00:33:56.150
Central sensitization
is where you

00:33:56.150 --> 00:33:59.270
have a chronic,
repetitive pain that

00:33:59.270 --> 00:34:03.590
causes actual physical
plastic changes to your brain.

00:34:03.590 --> 00:34:05.630
Then that causes other
parts of your brain

00:34:05.630 --> 00:34:10.040
to create problems, like
in the case of migraines,

00:34:10.040 --> 00:34:12.259
making blood vessels
open and close.

00:34:12.259 --> 00:34:13.909
WENDY JUDSON: Is that why the
visual disturbances can occur?

00:34:13.909 --> 00:34:14.480
DAVE SHIRAZI: That's right.

00:34:14.480 --> 00:34:15.380
That's [INAUDIBLE].

00:34:15.380 --> 00:34:16.543
Absolutely.

00:34:16.543 --> 00:34:17.960
But it could also
be other things.

00:34:17.960 --> 00:34:20.120
You can have burning
mouth syndrome.

00:34:20.120 --> 00:34:22.219
You could have
trigeminal neuralgia.

00:34:22.219 --> 00:34:25.310
These are all essentially
sensitized disorders.

00:34:25.310 --> 00:34:28.340
And what determines which
one you could potentially

00:34:28.340 --> 00:34:30.710
have is your genetics.

00:34:30.710 --> 00:34:34.909
But then it's what is creating
the response of your genetics

00:34:34.909 --> 00:34:36.067
to do that.

00:34:36.067 --> 00:34:37.400
Because your genes aren't just--

00:34:37.400 --> 00:34:39.530
I find the whole
argument of migraines

00:34:39.530 --> 00:34:42.050
being genetic only as
absolutely preposterous,

00:34:42.050 --> 00:34:46.190
because someone can go
their whole life, 40 years.

00:34:46.190 --> 00:34:48.620
They have, obviously, the
genetic markers for migraine.

00:34:48.620 --> 00:34:50.840
They never had a
single migraine.

00:34:50.840 --> 00:34:52.190
And then something changes.

00:34:52.190 --> 00:34:54.955
They change their diet, they
have sleep fragmentation,

00:34:54.955 --> 00:34:57.080
they get a jaw problem,
they have a dental problem,

00:34:57.080 --> 00:34:59.090
they have a sinus
problem, and then they

00:34:59.090 --> 00:35:01.460
start getting migraines.

00:35:01.460 --> 00:35:05.545
So we can't look at the
genetics as the cause of that.

00:35:05.545 --> 00:35:06.920
We have to look
at it and go, OK,

00:35:06.920 --> 00:35:10.460
what was it in their
environment that created that?

00:35:10.460 --> 00:35:13.250
And so migraine
is, if that is what

00:35:13.250 --> 00:35:16.250
your genetic predisposition
is, then having

00:35:16.250 --> 00:35:20.270
chronic inflammation or chronic
pain induced by your jaw,

00:35:20.270 --> 00:35:24.290
by a nasal airway issue, by fill
in the blank, anything that's

00:35:24.290 --> 00:35:26.270
connected to the
trigeminal nerve,

00:35:26.270 --> 00:35:28.160
can then create a migraine.

00:35:28.160 --> 00:35:30.965
WENDY JUDSON: Now, why is the
trigeminal nerve significant?

00:35:30.965 --> 00:35:32.090
I'm gonna go ahead through.

00:35:32.090 --> 00:35:35.450
DAVE SHIRAZI: It's an extremely
special cranial nerve.

00:35:35.450 --> 00:35:37.170
It's easily the biggest one.

00:35:37.170 --> 00:35:39.270
It's both sensory and motor.

00:35:39.270 --> 00:35:44.360
It anastomosis with
other cranial nerves.

00:35:44.360 --> 00:35:46.850
And it's just really
essential to our survival.

00:35:46.850 --> 00:35:50.600
It's related to our vision,
our nasal breathing,

00:35:50.600 --> 00:35:51.577
and our chewing.

00:35:51.577 --> 00:35:52.660
WENDY JUDSON: Anastomosis.

00:35:52.660 --> 00:35:53.030
Could you--

00:35:53.030 --> 00:35:54.197
DAVE SHIRAZI: Oh, I'm sorry.

00:35:54.197 --> 00:35:56.997
The word anastomosis means
kind of merging together.

00:35:56.997 --> 00:35:58.580
So you can have a
couple [INAUDIBLE]..

00:35:58.580 --> 00:35:59.955
Like for example,
along the face,

00:35:59.955 --> 00:36:03.350
an anastomosis with
the facial nerve.

00:36:03.350 --> 00:36:05.900
So you can have a
constant facial pain

00:36:05.900 --> 00:36:07.955
that then causes the
central sensitization

00:36:07.955 --> 00:36:10.310
in the trigeminal nerve,
because they're all connected.

00:36:10.310 --> 00:36:12.560
WENDY JUDSON: Right, there's
nine nerves that actually

00:36:12.560 --> 00:36:13.727
pass through the jaw, right?

00:36:13.727 --> 00:36:15.227
DAVE SHIRAZI: Yeah,
there's several.

00:36:15.227 --> 00:36:15.892
That's right.

00:36:15.892 --> 00:36:16.630
That's right.

00:36:16.630 --> 00:36:18.630
There's several.

00:36:18.630 --> 00:36:22.590
WENDY JUDSON: So this one goes
back to our reptilian brain,

00:36:22.590 --> 00:36:24.240
as do most of the
cranial nerves.

00:36:24.240 --> 00:36:27.377
But there, there's the
anastomosis, right?

00:36:27.377 --> 00:36:29.460
DAVE SHIRAZI: Well, no
that's not the anastomosis.

00:36:29.460 --> 00:36:33.150
The anastomosis is really
predominantly happening

00:36:33.150 --> 00:36:36.570
outside where it starts
to kind of merge together.

00:36:36.570 --> 00:36:38.490
Over here, you can
kind of see how close

00:36:38.490 --> 00:36:40.200
they are to one
another and how they're

00:36:40.200 --> 00:36:43.250
so close to the brain stem.

00:36:43.250 --> 00:36:45.000
You see the olfactory,
you see the second.

00:36:45.000 --> 00:36:45.950
You see they all
just come together.

00:36:45.950 --> 00:36:46.640
WENDY JUDSON: Yeah,
it's a big one

00:36:46.640 --> 00:36:48.138
compared to everything else.

00:36:48.138 --> 00:36:49.680
DAVE SHIRAZI: It's
much, much bigger.

00:36:49.680 --> 00:36:51.138
And that should
tell you something.

00:36:51.138 --> 00:36:53.960
The brain is all
about real estate.

00:36:53.960 --> 00:36:56.600
Anything that's in
the brain is there

00:36:56.600 --> 00:36:59.710
because it really,
really needs to be.

00:36:59.710 --> 00:37:04.200
So if we have something that
takes up a lot of real estate,

00:37:04.200 --> 00:37:07.613
that means the brain puts
a lot of value on it.

00:37:07.613 --> 00:37:08.970
Does that make sense?

00:37:08.970 --> 00:37:09.762
WENDY JUDSON: Yeah.

00:37:11.660 --> 00:37:14.480
And then I put this
one in from your deck,

00:37:14.480 --> 00:37:17.330
because so often
times people are

00:37:17.330 --> 00:37:20.600
coming to me with head,
neck, shoulder pain

00:37:20.600 --> 00:37:22.820
because they've been
at the computer.

00:37:22.820 --> 00:37:26.810
And yet it could all be
related to the jaw, or at least

00:37:26.810 --> 00:37:29.060
a good portion of it.

00:37:29.060 --> 00:37:31.920
So addressing that could
help a lot of this.

00:37:31.920 --> 00:37:33.170
DAVE SHIRAZI: Yes, absolutely.

00:37:33.170 --> 00:37:35.967
Just stopping the clenching
or stopping your ability

00:37:35.967 --> 00:37:38.300
to clench during the day while
you're working and trying

00:37:38.300 --> 00:37:41.030
to control the situation
will go a long way

00:37:41.030 --> 00:37:43.000
to relieve either
the muscle pain here

00:37:43.000 --> 00:37:47.590
as it refers to other parts of
your body as trigger points.

00:37:47.590 --> 00:37:49.840
WENDY JUDSON: Now,
there's another picture

00:37:49.840 --> 00:37:52.250
of the difference of
a before and after.

00:37:52.250 --> 00:37:55.293
What was this patient given?

00:37:55.293 --> 00:37:56.710
DAVE SHIRAZI: So
this is a patient

00:37:56.710 --> 00:38:01.780
that had both a sleep apnea
issue and a TMJ issue.

00:38:01.780 --> 00:38:03.770
So we're looking
at a number things.

00:38:03.770 --> 00:38:05.650
So in my-- there
are many reasons

00:38:05.650 --> 00:38:08.760
why we can have
forward head posture.

00:38:08.760 --> 00:38:10.600
One, the ergonomics,
like you mentioned

00:38:10.600 --> 00:38:14.360
is, in today's
climate, a big problem.

00:38:14.360 --> 00:38:18.040
But if you're mouth breathing,
in order to mouth breathe,

00:38:18.040 --> 00:38:21.250
you just unconsciously
bring your jaw

00:38:21.250 --> 00:38:23.800
forward so you can breathe
through your mouth.

00:38:23.800 --> 00:38:25.300
Does that make sense?

00:38:25.300 --> 00:38:26.800
Because when you're
nasal breathing,

00:38:26.800 --> 00:38:29.633
the air has a nice
little passage of flow.

00:38:29.633 --> 00:38:31.300
But when you're mouth
breathing, the air

00:38:31.300 --> 00:38:33.970
has to make a 90 degree shunt.

00:38:33.970 --> 00:38:37.510
And you have to kind of open
it to make it more arced.

00:38:37.510 --> 00:38:38.600
Does that make sense?

00:38:38.600 --> 00:38:40.810
So we just unconsciously do it.

00:38:40.810 --> 00:38:43.570
The brain has many
reflexes built

00:38:43.570 --> 00:38:47.090
into it, many
protective mechanisms

00:38:47.090 --> 00:38:50.920
so it doesn't have to
constantly be reminded of things

00:38:50.920 --> 00:38:52.760
that it doesn't
consider important.

00:38:52.760 --> 00:38:55.840
So if you walked into a
room that smelled very, very

00:38:55.840 --> 00:38:58.840
bad, after about
five minutes, you

00:38:58.840 --> 00:39:01.870
stop realizing that
there is a smell.

00:39:01.870 --> 00:39:05.650
Because the frontal lobe
doesn't need that information.

00:39:05.650 --> 00:39:08.660
That's not relevant to your
survival, at that point.

00:39:08.660 --> 00:39:10.450
However, if you have
a sprained ankle,

00:39:10.450 --> 00:39:13.120
your brain needs to
unconsciously know

00:39:13.120 --> 00:39:15.640
that if we have to run
away in an emergency,

00:39:15.640 --> 00:39:18.250
we'd put all the weight
on the other leg.

00:39:18.250 --> 00:39:21.400
So you oftentimes don't
have to think about limping,

00:39:21.400 --> 00:39:23.620
because your brain
automatically does it.

00:39:23.620 --> 00:39:25.083
Same thing with breathing.

00:39:25.083 --> 00:39:26.500
When we have to
breathe, the brain

00:39:26.500 --> 00:39:29.650
can't constantly be reminded
that, oh, by the way,

00:39:29.650 --> 00:39:32.830
hold your head here because
your nose is blocked.

00:39:32.830 --> 00:39:34.450
It just automatically does it.

00:39:34.450 --> 00:39:36.460
And then we come to
swallowing, which

00:39:36.460 --> 00:39:39.940
is what we do 2,000
to 3,000 times a day.

00:39:39.940 --> 00:39:42.880
When we do it, our
teeth come in contact.

00:39:42.880 --> 00:39:44.560
And if we have a
jaw problem, that's

00:39:44.560 --> 00:39:47.020
when we're putting the
most amount of pressure

00:39:47.020 --> 00:39:50.410
into the nerves of the
jaw during the day.

00:39:50.410 --> 00:39:53.920
So then what the brain
can do is unconsciously,

00:39:53.920 --> 00:39:56.920
reflexively hold the jaw
a little bit different,

00:39:56.920 --> 00:39:59.890
a little bit away from where
the pain is coming from.

00:39:59.890 --> 00:40:02.230
But then we have
to swallow again.

00:40:02.230 --> 00:40:05.260
So by the way, I just
recently learned myself

00:40:05.260 --> 00:40:08.980
within the last couple of years,
swallowing is a survival reflex

00:40:08.980 --> 00:40:12.540
because it tells the airway
that it's safe to breathe.

00:40:12.540 --> 00:40:14.740
The saliva that passes
tells the brain,

00:40:14.740 --> 00:40:16.240
ah, we're good to breathe now.

00:40:16.240 --> 00:40:18.040
Carry on.

00:40:18.040 --> 00:40:21.340
So when we swallow and
our teeth come together

00:40:21.340 --> 00:40:24.340
and the jaw goes back there, if
we have a jaw problem, if you

00:40:24.340 --> 00:40:28.390
have a TMJ disorder that's hurt
hurting, much like the limping

00:40:28.390 --> 00:40:30.700
on the other leg, our jaw goes--

00:40:30.700 --> 00:40:33.958
and by exaggeration,
our jaw goes forward.

00:40:33.958 --> 00:40:36.250
But then we have to swallow
again, and when we swallow,

00:40:36.250 --> 00:40:37.540
our teeth have to contact.

00:40:37.540 --> 00:40:41.485
So when we do, we do a
pigeon maneuver like this.

00:40:41.485 --> 00:40:43.360
So if you can imagine
a couple thousand times

00:40:43.360 --> 00:40:45.620
a day of doing this
pigeon maneuver,

00:40:45.620 --> 00:40:46.860
you're going to have--

00:40:46.860 --> 00:40:48.850
WENDY JUDSON: You're gonna end
up with forward head posture.

00:40:48.850 --> 00:40:50.230
DAVE SHIRAZI: Potentially, yeah.

00:40:50.230 --> 00:40:51.688
WENDY JUDSON: And
the muscle memory

00:40:51.688 --> 00:40:54.190
that is associated with
that clenching, too, right?

00:40:54.190 --> 00:40:55.565
DAVE SHIRAZI:
Well, the clenching

00:40:55.565 --> 00:40:59.440
that we do is with our
teeth together in the back.

00:40:59.440 --> 00:41:03.640
So the CPAP, I just want you
to know, I am not anti CPAP.

00:41:03.640 --> 00:41:05.380
The CPAP works.

00:41:05.380 --> 00:41:11.650
It has something like a 98.7
success rate in treating

00:41:11.650 --> 00:41:14.510
sleep apnea, period.

00:41:14.510 --> 00:41:19.320
The problem with
CPAP is that it has

00:41:19.320 --> 00:41:23.680
a huge failure in patient
compliance, like 40% to 60%,

00:41:23.680 --> 00:41:26.860
depending on which
study you look at.

00:41:26.860 --> 00:41:29.320
I am not a fan, I
should say, I am not

00:41:29.320 --> 00:41:31.240
a fan of CPAP in children.

00:41:31.240 --> 00:41:33.980
In the growing child,
I'm very much against it,

00:41:33.980 --> 00:41:36.820
unless we're talking about a
central problem potentially

00:41:36.820 --> 00:41:42.250
or some other kind of either
brain or genetic malformation.

00:41:42.250 --> 00:41:43.810
But for the majority
of the people,

00:41:43.810 --> 00:41:46.160
if you can tolerate
the CPAP as an adult,

00:41:46.160 --> 00:41:48.652
I'm never going to tell
anyone not to do it.

00:41:48.652 --> 00:41:51.110
WENDY JUDSON: But let's look
at what the other options are.

00:41:51.110 --> 00:41:53.068
DAVE SHIRAZI: The other
options are exist, too.

00:41:53.068 --> 00:41:54.520
You have oral
appliances that do--

00:41:54.520 --> 00:41:59.770
so whereas a CPAP is what
we call a pneumatic splint,

00:41:59.770 --> 00:42:01.480
it literally pushes--

00:42:01.480 --> 00:42:04.240
the air pressure is not
designed to help you breathe.

00:42:04.240 --> 00:42:07.120
The air pressure is designed
to blow up your airway,

00:42:07.120 --> 00:42:11.500
like you blow up a balloon,
to keep your airway patent.

00:42:11.500 --> 00:42:13.180
And so your inhale
and your exhale kind

00:42:13.180 --> 00:42:15.190
of fights against the pressure.

00:42:15.190 --> 00:42:18.250
But at the same time, it doesn't
allow the airway to collapse,

00:42:18.250 --> 00:42:20.070
because you're blowing it open.

00:42:20.070 --> 00:42:22.810
You're, basically, you're
allowing the air pressure

00:42:22.810 --> 00:42:25.060
to blow your tongue forward.

00:42:25.060 --> 00:42:26.680
Does that make sense?

00:42:26.680 --> 00:42:30.460
So an oral appliance is
actually called a splint,

00:42:30.460 --> 00:42:33.450
like a physical splint as
opposed to a pneumatic splint.

00:42:33.450 --> 00:42:35.660
Well, we can potentially
bring the tongue forward,

00:42:35.660 --> 00:42:38.470
bring the jaw forward,
lift the tongue,

00:42:38.470 --> 00:42:40.960
like instruct the tongue to
go on the roof of the mouth,

00:42:40.960 --> 00:42:43.790
help with the nasal breathing
by opening up the nasal valve.

00:42:43.790 --> 00:42:45.790
WENDY JUDSON: Now, we're
talking about this type

00:42:45.790 --> 00:42:48.430
of a splint, not the kind that
they form around your teeth.

00:42:48.430 --> 00:42:49.870
DAVE SHIRAZI: No, that's
the kind I'm talking about.

00:42:49.870 --> 00:42:51.850
The kind that's custom
made to your teeth.

00:42:51.850 --> 00:42:54.310
Now, this kind of device
that you have showing

00:42:54.310 --> 00:42:58.090
is what's called an ALF, an
Advanced Lightwire Functional.

00:42:58.090 --> 00:43:01.840
This is a kind of what we call
functional orthodontic device

00:43:01.840 --> 00:43:05.650
that we can use in children
to expand their palate

00:43:05.650 --> 00:43:10.558
and literally cure
sleep apnea in most.

00:43:10.558 --> 00:43:12.850
It also acts, by the way, as
a myofunctional appliance,

00:43:12.850 --> 00:43:15.880
because that little center
loop that you see on there

00:43:15.880 --> 00:43:18.970
actually helps train
the tongue where to be.

00:43:18.970 --> 00:43:21.520
If we get a little
hair in our mouth,

00:43:21.520 --> 00:43:23.200
we go nuts until we get it out.

00:43:23.200 --> 00:43:26.080
The tongue becomes acutely
aware of that tiny little piece

00:43:26.080 --> 00:43:28.980
of hair, because we have so
many nerves in our tongue.

00:43:28.980 --> 00:43:32.650
The tongue actually seeks
out that loop and it

00:43:32.650 --> 00:43:35.770
helps train the tongue
on where to swallow 24/7.

00:43:35.770 --> 00:43:41.750
But then we can activate it and
then develop the palate itself.

00:43:41.750 --> 00:43:44.980
WENDY JUDSON: So if I were to
use this instead of my splint

00:43:44.980 --> 00:43:46.990
that I have, because
I find my splint,

00:43:46.990 --> 00:43:48.612
I just want to
clench more on it.

00:43:48.612 --> 00:43:49.570
DAVE SHIRAZI: Yeah, OK.

00:43:49.570 --> 00:43:51.517
WENDY JUDSON: So could
I stop clenching?

00:43:51.517 --> 00:43:52.600
DAVE SHIRAZI: Potentially.

00:43:52.600 --> 00:43:54.610
So let's discuss
that for a moment.

00:43:54.610 --> 00:43:56.110
There were studies
done, and I think

00:43:56.110 --> 00:43:58.180
you may even have
the slide here,

00:43:58.180 --> 00:44:01.960
where they took subjects
that had sleep apnea

00:44:01.960 --> 00:44:04.750
and clenched their teeth
and didn't use their CPAP.

00:44:04.750 --> 00:44:06.550
They used a night guard instead.

00:44:06.550 --> 00:44:10.590
And we found that it
made their apnea worse.

00:44:10.590 --> 00:44:12.520
And then they also
clenched worse,

00:44:12.520 --> 00:44:15.490
because we found that they
were clenching harder in order

00:44:15.490 --> 00:44:18.530
to breathe, is the presumption.

00:44:18.530 --> 00:44:21.730
So in this, we actually
have seen studies just

00:44:21.730 --> 00:44:25.480
with myofunctional therapy where
there is less clenching just

00:44:25.480 --> 00:44:28.090
from knowing where
you're tongue is.

00:44:28.090 --> 00:44:31.870
With the ALF, we're
also finding that it

00:44:31.870 --> 00:44:34.300
changes your autonomic tone.

00:44:34.300 --> 00:44:36.610
It allows your
sympathetic nervous system

00:44:36.610 --> 00:44:41.020
to shift more to parasympathetic
and allows more calm,

00:44:41.020 --> 00:44:43.840
which allows more natural
physiological reactions

00:44:43.840 --> 00:44:46.465
to happen and less of a
response to the clenching.

00:44:46.465 --> 00:44:47.960
Does that make sense?

00:44:47.960 --> 00:44:49.210
WENDY JUDSON: It does.

00:44:49.210 --> 00:44:52.980
I'm wondering, Cleo, do you want
to speak about your experience,

00:44:52.980 --> 00:44:55.700
since you do actually
have this device?

00:44:55.700 --> 00:44:57.070
CLEO: I do.

00:44:57.070 --> 00:44:59.950
Yeah, so I have an
ALF device installed.

00:44:59.950 --> 00:45:02.660
One thing that you said
actually was that you're like--

00:45:02.660 --> 00:45:04.140
you can put it in children.

00:45:04.140 --> 00:45:06.640
I'm an adult child, apparently,
because I have one of these,

00:45:06.640 --> 00:45:08.390
too.

00:45:08.390 --> 00:45:11.500
And what it's been
doing is it's definitely

00:45:11.500 --> 00:45:15.220
physically widening my palate,
which has been amazing.

00:45:15.220 --> 00:45:18.760
But even before I was doing
anything, when he first

00:45:18.760 --> 00:45:22.300
installs it, you
don't have any--

00:45:22.300 --> 00:45:25.810
he doesn't try to
make it do anything.

00:45:25.810 --> 00:45:29.300
You just let your body
adapt to it initially.

00:45:29.300 --> 00:45:30.760
And it's exactly
what he was saying

00:45:30.760 --> 00:45:32.890
about how my tongue
was immediately

00:45:32.890 --> 00:45:38.080
attracted to the metal
part on top right there.

00:45:38.080 --> 00:45:39.970
And then I started
sleeping with my tongue

00:45:39.970 --> 00:45:41.887
on the roof of my mouth,
and all of a sudden I

00:45:41.887 --> 00:45:43.670
was sleeping through the night.

00:45:43.670 --> 00:45:45.790
I used to think that--

00:45:45.790 --> 00:45:47.770
I was waking up three
or four times a night

00:45:47.770 --> 00:45:49.270
to go to the bathroom,
and I thought

00:45:49.270 --> 00:45:51.520
it was because I need to
cut off my water earlier

00:45:51.520 --> 00:45:53.620
and earlier at night,
and it wasn't helping.

00:45:53.620 --> 00:45:56.080
And of course, I'm blaming
the cat for some of this,

00:45:56.080 --> 00:45:57.560
too, because he's 21.

00:45:57.560 --> 00:45:59.980
I mean, he's kind of a pain.

00:45:59.980 --> 00:46:02.205
But it turned out
that it wasn't--

00:46:02.205 --> 00:46:04.330
I wasn't waking up because
of the bladder problems.

00:46:04.330 --> 00:46:07.060
I was waking up and
noticing that I should

00:46:07.060 --> 00:46:09.970
go to the bathroom and thinking
that that was the causation,

00:46:09.970 --> 00:46:11.140
but it wasn't the cause.

00:46:11.140 --> 00:46:14.050
It was actually that I just
was not getting good sleep.

00:46:14.050 --> 00:46:16.960
And I was getting nine
and a half hours of sleep

00:46:16.960 --> 00:46:19.340
and waking up tired
thinking, well,

00:46:19.340 --> 00:46:21.340
I'm just going to spend
more than 1/3 of my life

00:46:21.340 --> 00:46:23.793
in bed, because I can't
seem to get enough sleep.

00:46:23.793 --> 00:46:25.210
And now that I
have this device, I

00:46:25.210 --> 00:46:29.150
wake up after seven, seven and a
half hours and I'm ready to go.

00:46:29.150 --> 00:46:30.610
So it's been pretty--

00:46:30.610 --> 00:46:32.200
personally, from my
perspective, it's

00:46:32.200 --> 00:46:36.070
been very effective at dealing
with my snoring and my bruxism.

00:46:36.070 --> 00:46:39.310
That was basically what
we were trying to target.

00:46:39.310 --> 00:46:42.070
And I went to see
Dr. Shirazi because I

00:46:42.070 --> 00:46:43.450
used to have a
night guard, which

00:46:43.450 --> 00:46:46.557
would prevent me from
grinding my teeth at night.

00:46:46.557 --> 00:46:48.640
Didn't prevent me from
grinding my teeth at night.

00:46:48.640 --> 00:46:51.760
What it did was it prevented me
from doing damage to my teeth

00:46:51.760 --> 00:46:53.140
when I was grinding at night.

00:46:53.140 --> 00:46:54.360
It didn't help me sleep.

00:46:54.360 --> 00:46:57.480
