my nose more?

00:57:51.590 --> 00:57:52.665
Is that kind of the idea?

00:57:52.665 --> 00:57:54.290
DAVE SHIRAZI: That's
one of the easiest

00:57:54.290 --> 00:57:56.390
thing within your control.

00:57:56.390 --> 00:58:00.770
Putting the tongue right
behind your two front teeth

00:58:00.770 --> 00:58:03.260
where that bump is,
practicing swallowing

00:58:03.260 --> 00:58:05.030
and this kind of
rhythmic motion,

00:58:05.030 --> 00:58:07.980
and focusing on breathing
through your nose.

00:58:07.980 --> 00:58:10.460
Breathe Right strips, if
you have nasal obstruction,

00:58:10.460 --> 00:58:13.640
something like a Breathe Right
strip or a nasal dilator,

00:58:13.640 --> 00:58:16.220
is very helpful to
help to force you

00:58:16.220 --> 00:58:18.060
to breathe through your nose.

00:58:18.060 --> 00:58:20.930
Sometimes we recommend
taping the lips shut, again,

00:58:20.930 --> 00:58:23.320
to force you to breathe
through your nose.

00:58:23.320 --> 00:58:26.270
Most of my patients that I
recommend that I want in a V

00:58:26.270 --> 00:58:28.610
so that you can actually
have a little escape window.

00:58:28.610 --> 00:58:31.910
But you have a beard, so
you can't really do that.

00:58:31.910 --> 00:58:34.225
Those are the things that
are within your control.

00:58:34.225 --> 00:58:35.600
AUDIENCE: What
about guaifenesin?

00:58:35.600 --> 00:58:36.600
DAVE SHIRAZI: I'm sorry?

00:58:36.600 --> 00:58:39.287
AUDIENCE: What about
guaifenesin to help remove any--

00:58:39.287 --> 00:58:40.370
DAVE SHIRAZI: Guaifenesin?

00:58:40.370 --> 00:58:41.720
AUDIENCE: Yeah, the Mucinex.

00:58:41.720 --> 00:58:42.360
DAVE SHIRAZI: Oh, Mucinex.

00:58:42.360 --> 00:58:44.000
OK, so if that's
an issue, if you're

00:58:44.000 --> 00:58:47.630
getting excess mucus
secretions through your nose,

00:58:47.630 --> 00:58:48.380
yeah, that's fine.

00:58:48.380 --> 00:58:53.570
So for example, things like
nasal steroids, for example,

00:58:53.570 --> 00:58:59.300
it will shrink up your nasal
breathing by almost 100%

00:58:59.300 --> 00:59:00.800
for four hours.

00:59:00.800 --> 00:59:04.280
And then it has a
drastic rebound effect

00:59:04.280 --> 00:59:07.140
where your nose swells up
and you can't breathe at all

00:59:07.140 --> 00:59:08.750
after it wears off.

00:59:08.750 --> 00:59:11.210
And plus, the preliminary
studies showed that it actually

00:59:11.210 --> 00:59:13.760
changes your brainwaves,
your EEG signals,

00:59:13.760 --> 00:59:15.890
from the steroid that's
in it, we presume.

00:59:15.890 --> 00:59:19.880
So I'm not a fan of
nasal corticosteroids.

00:59:19.880 --> 00:59:22.280
If someone was an
athlete and they

00:59:22.280 --> 00:59:24.773
were allowed to do
nasal corticosteroids

00:59:24.773 --> 00:59:26.690
and we want them to
breathe through their nose

00:59:26.690 --> 00:59:29.510
and they're having a flu or
something that stops them,

00:59:29.510 --> 00:59:31.100
OK, go ahead, do it.

00:59:31.100 --> 00:59:34.850
But to me, it's not
a lifelong solution.

00:59:34.850 --> 00:59:37.700
I personally make
my own nasal spray

00:59:37.700 --> 00:59:39.980
with essential oils, just
over-the-counter essential

00:59:39.980 --> 00:59:40.700
oils.

00:59:40.700 --> 00:59:44.910
And just anecdotally-- I haven't
done a study, anecdotally--

00:59:44.910 --> 00:59:49.070
80% of my patients that were
essentially addicted to FLONASE

00:59:49.070 --> 00:59:50.570
or some kind of
nasal corticosteroid

00:59:50.570 --> 00:59:53.510
have put it down and
switched to my nasal spray

00:59:53.510 --> 00:59:56.760
and only refer to the
FLONASE as an emergency.

00:59:56.760 --> 00:59:59.000
And in my personal
opinion, steroids

00:59:59.000 --> 01:00:02.450
should only be used
in an emergency.

01:00:02.450 --> 01:00:06.262
It depletes our adrenals.

01:00:06.262 --> 01:00:07.220
There are side effects.

01:00:07.220 --> 01:00:09.440
You're paying for
it later when you

01:00:09.440 --> 01:00:12.560
have chronic corticosteroid
use, whether it's

01:00:12.560 --> 01:00:15.200
topical cream,
nasal, or otherwise.

01:00:15.200 --> 01:00:16.850
It's fine for short term.

01:00:16.850 --> 01:00:18.050
A week is fine.

01:00:18.050 --> 01:00:21.530
But we should only be using
it on an emergency basis,

01:00:21.530 --> 01:00:24.620
in my opinion, if you
have no other choice.

01:00:24.620 --> 01:00:26.930
CLEO: And back to what you
said about the guaifenesin,

01:00:26.930 --> 01:00:28.550
I would say that if
you're chronically

01:00:28.550 --> 01:00:31.815
having to use something like
Mucinex or a decongestant,

01:00:31.815 --> 01:00:33.440
there might be
something else going on.

01:00:33.440 --> 01:00:35.360
There might be some
allergy going on,

01:00:35.360 --> 01:00:38.810
whether it's an environmental
allergy or a food allergy,

01:00:38.810 --> 01:00:42.050
that you can investigate to see
why you're not breathing well

01:00:42.050 --> 01:00:42.690
at night.

01:00:42.690 --> 01:00:44.690
And it might even be the
case that it's actually

01:00:44.690 --> 01:00:46.940
happening during the day,
too, and you don't notice it

01:00:46.940 --> 01:00:49.790
because you're actually able
to drain your sinuses better

01:00:49.790 --> 01:00:51.780
during the day.

01:00:51.780 --> 01:00:54.230
But at night when you're
lying down and everything

01:00:54.230 --> 01:00:55.258
can get clogged up.

01:00:55.258 --> 01:00:56.550
DAVE SHIRAZI: Excellent points.

01:00:56.550 --> 01:00:58.883
CLEO: I think that we have
to take Dr. Shirazi to lunch.

01:00:58.883 --> 01:01:00.650
Is there one more question?

01:01:00.650 --> 01:01:01.310
OK.

01:01:01.310 --> 01:01:02.290
One more question.

01:01:02.290 --> 01:01:03.980
Wait, there's a fight.

01:01:03.980 --> 01:01:06.050
Arm wrestle.

01:01:06.050 --> 01:01:08.180
OK.

01:01:08.180 --> 01:01:09.430
AUDIENCE: Actually, three.

01:01:09.430 --> 01:01:11.270
DAVE SHIRAZI: Oh, OK.

01:01:11.270 --> 01:01:13.460
AUDIENCE: How long
do you recommend

01:01:13.460 --> 01:01:18.100
breastfeed to fix baby's
breathing problem for life?

01:01:18.100 --> 01:01:20.780
DAVE SHIRAZI: So, I mean,
obviously there hasn't

01:01:20.780 --> 01:01:23.690
been any studies on that.

01:01:23.690 --> 01:01:28.550
We definitely want-- to me,
the absolute minimum in my mind

01:01:28.550 --> 01:01:30.080
is one year.

01:01:30.080 --> 01:01:33.040
We breastfed-- my
wife, we, my wife

01:01:33.040 --> 01:01:37.010
breastfed our son
for almost two years.

01:01:37.010 --> 01:01:41.640
If someone did it for two to
three, I'm OK with it, too.

01:01:41.640 --> 01:01:44.400
When teeth come
into the picture,

01:01:44.400 --> 01:01:47.630
we're supposed to
use those teeth.

01:01:47.630 --> 01:01:52.310
So we're supposed to have all
our teeth by age two or three.

01:01:52.310 --> 01:01:54.080
So all our baby
teeth, I should say.

01:01:54.080 --> 01:01:57.320
We should be chewing food with
those teeth when they come out.

01:01:57.320 --> 01:02:02.330
Because whereas the swallowing
develops our palate this way,

01:02:02.330 --> 01:02:04.760
our chewing muscles
develop our jaws

01:02:04.760 --> 01:02:07.700
in this direction, the
vertical direction.

01:02:07.700 --> 01:02:09.597
So I often see
this in my office.

01:02:09.597 --> 01:02:11.430
Someone will come and
see me and they look--

01:02:11.430 --> 01:02:13.320
I don't mean this
in a derogatory way

01:02:13.320 --> 01:02:16.010
at all-- they look like a
Japanese animation character,

01:02:16.010 --> 01:02:19.580
because they have big eyes and
a teeny, teeny, teeny mouth.

01:02:19.580 --> 01:02:21.730
I know that at a
very young age, they

01:02:21.730 --> 01:02:23.660
ate predominantly soft food.

01:02:23.660 --> 01:02:26.490
They did not put their
[INAUDIBLE] activity

01:02:26.490 --> 01:02:27.710
to good use.

01:02:27.710 --> 01:02:29.630
And when they have a
little teeny mouth,

01:02:29.630 --> 01:02:32.330
their jaw is a little bit
smaller, and they come back up

01:02:32.330 --> 01:02:37.620
and they have more propensity
for a TMJ problem later on.

01:02:37.620 --> 01:02:41.030
So in my mind, it's at least
a year, two years better.

01:02:41.030 --> 01:02:44.390
Plus the other aspect
of it is the first year

01:02:44.390 --> 01:02:49.790
of an infant's life, they do
not have a mature immune system.

01:02:49.790 --> 01:02:54.800
They get 100% of their
immunity from their gut.

01:02:54.800 --> 01:02:57.560
So whether you're breastfeeding
and giving it to them

01:02:57.560 --> 01:03:00.380
or you're adding probiotics
to their formula--

01:03:00.380 --> 01:03:03.330
and hopefully you're using a
goat milk-based formula over

01:03:03.330 --> 01:03:04.490
a soy--

01:03:04.490 --> 01:03:06.380
that's how they're getting it.

01:03:06.380 --> 01:03:10.370
They're sincerely not getting
immunity for any length of time

01:03:10.370 --> 01:03:14.572
from anything else other
than from their gut.

01:03:14.572 --> 01:03:16.030
CLEO: Thank you so
much for coming,

01:03:16.030 --> 01:03:17.620
and we really
appreciate the talk.

01:03:17.620 --> 01:03:18.520
Thank you.

01:03:18.520 --> 01:03:20.970
[APPLAUSE]

